---

## Abstract

The global Ayurvedic medicine market, valued at over USD 10 billion, suffers from rampant adulteration, opaque supply chains, and absence of technologically enforced quality governance. This paper presents **VaidyaChain**, a full-stack, blockchain-powered Progressive Web Application (PWA) designed to provide end-to-end traceability of Ayurvedic medicinal herbs from farm origin to consumer verification. VaidyaChain uniquely integrates eleven role-based dashboards, client-side blockchain simulation with hash-chaining, Ethereum-style smart contracts for automated quality enforcement and parametric crop insurance, GPS-verified geospatial collection logging, spectroscopy-based lab visualization, DNA banking for endangered herb preservation, multilingual support (English, Hindi, Gujarati), AI-powered multilingual chatbot assistance, QR-code product authentication, and waste-to-value agricultural sustainability metrics — all within a zero-backend JavaScript architecture. This paper details the system architecture, novel feature set, implementation design, and its differentiated contribution to existing blockchain supply chain literature. Our evaluation demonstrates that VaidyaChain addresses critical gaps no existing open-source framework has resolved for the Ayurvedic domain.

**Keywords:** Blockchain, Ayurveda, Supply Chain Traceability, Smart Contracts, Parametric Insurance, DNA Banking, Progressive Web App, Multi-Stakeholder Platform

---

## I. Introduction

The Ayurvedic and herbal medicine industry faces a multi-dimensional crisis of trust and transparency. Studies by the WHO indicate that approximately 25% of herbal medicinal products worldwide are adulterated or mislabeled [1]. For India's Ayurvedic sector — which involves millions of farmers, hundreds of processing labs, and thousands of manufacturers — the absence of a verifiable, tamper-proof chain of custody from harvesting to consumer end-point constitutes both a public health risk and an economic hazard.

Blockchain technology, by virtue of its immutability, decentralization, and cryptographic integrity, offers a promising substrate for solving supply chain opacity [2]. However, existing implementations for pharmaceutical or food supply chains (e.g., IBM Food Trust for food, MediLedger for pharmaceuticals) do not address the unique requirements of the Ayurvedic domain, which demands:

1. **Botanical identity verification** (species-level tracking, not just batch tracking)
2. **Multi-party stakeholder workflows** spanning farmers, testing laboratories, manufacturers, distributors, and consumers
3. **Traditional knowledge context** combining scientific quality metrics with Ayurvedic classification
4. **Rural accessibility**, including low-literacy farmers in native Indian languages
5. **Parametric smart contract insurance** that automates payout for crop/quality losses
6. **Genetic preservation** of endangered medicinal herb varieties

VaidyaChain is the first known system to holistically address all of these simultaneously. This paper makes the following contributions:

- A complete system architecture for a multi-stakeholder Ayurvedic supply blockchain
- Novel integration of parametric insurance smart contracts into agricultural supply chains
- First implementation of DNA banking for medicinal herb genetic preservation on a blockchain platform
- A client-side blockchain simulation approach enabling zero-cost deployment with full cryptographic guarantees
- Demonstrated multilingual AI chatbot integration for supply chain guidance in regional Indian languages

The remainder of this paper is organized as follows: Section II reviews related work; Section III presents the system architecture; Section IV describes the module implementations; Section V discusses novel contributions and differentiation; Section VI presents evaluation; Section VII concludes.

---

## II. Related Work

### A. Blockchain in Food and Pharmaceutical Supply Chains

Tian (2017) [3] proposed an agri-food supply chain traceability system using RFID and blockchain but did not incorporate smart contract automation or consumer-facing portals. Sunny et al. (2020) [4] demonstrated blockchain for pharmaceutical tracking. However, these solutions focused on generic supply chains, lacking domain-specific features for the botanical/Ayurvedic context.

### B. Smart Contracts in Insurance

Blockchain-based parametric insurance using smart contracts has been studied in the context of flight delays (Etherisc) and crop coverage (Oxfam's Acre Africa project) [5]. However, no published work applies parametric triggers directly integrated with quality test data from a supply chain's own laboratory module to auto-approve insurance claims.

### C. Existing Herb Traceability Platforms

Existing platforms like TraceLink (pharmaceutical) and OriginTrail address supply chain traceability but: (a) are not open access, (b) require centralized servers and subscription fees, (c) do not support native Indian languages, and (d) lack integrated insurance, DNA banking, or waste-management modules.

### D. Gap Analysis

| Feature | IBM Food Trust | MediLedger | OriginTrail | **VaidyaChain** |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Ayurveda-specific | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Multilingual (Hindi/Gujarati) | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Parametric Insurance SC | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| DNA Banking | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Zero-backend / PWA | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| QR Consumer Verification | Partial | ❌ | Partial | ✅ |
| AI Chatbot (Multilingual) | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |
| Waste Management Module | ❌ | ❌ | ❌ | ✅ |

